comment_data.body:
@hrishikesh-kadam These issues are reported by Android Studio as it starts up and are unrelated to the Flutter plugin; the plugin is just passing along the messages. 

Where were these messages reported for you? We see them when we start IntelliJ in a debugger and then click 'Open for editing.." there; they are reported in the console of the debug tool window.

I first noticed it after adding dev channel to test `59.0.3-dev.2`.
I could see it in the bottom right corner as below - 

![Screenshot from 2021-07-20 01-46-57](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8739924/126228931-6f8329d1-f58b-4a6a-a2d0-0c8ca83be54c.png)

So after clicking "See details and submit report" I saw this window - 

![Screenshot from 2021-07-20 02-54-44](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8739924/126229554-9259c528-8830-40ef-8dd6-b321d762bc0f.png)

From which I created this single issue from those 4 errors.

Also, I can see these errors in the console of the debug window.

All these errors are pointing at [OpenInAndroidStudioAction.java:235](https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/blob/890c07deec9f86420a93200a02626a8a057d0aaa/src/io/flutter/actions/OpenInAndroidStudioAction.java#L235).

The fact that we are reporting those errors using LOG.error seems like a mistake. We should instead surface the error via
`FlutterMessages.showError`
or similar. This stack trace isn't really useful. The real message is the error message reported by android studio when it attempted to launch and perhaps failed? The other option is that while these messages are sent to stderr they are ignorable. For your case, did Android Studio still startup successfully. You could use LOG.warn or LOG.info to log these messages but not distract the user with them.

@jacob314 As mentioned earlier, Android Studio does start correctly at the exact line and column.
I thought of just reporting the errors.

@hrishikesh-kadam Thanks for taking the time to report these errors. However, these are not caused by the Flutter plugin. The plugin is just passing along information reported by Android Studio when it starts up in the debugger. These messages are also reported by the production version but you only see them if you look in the log file.

title: Exceptions reported by IntelliJ IDEA after clicking `Open for Editing Android Studio`
